L
T
V
\mathbb R
L(v) = 0
T (v) = 0.
T = cL
c.
L\ne0.
L(V)
1.
\exists~\alpha\in V
L(\alpha)\ne0.
L(V)=\langle L(\alpha)\rangle.
c=\dfrac{T(\alpha)}{L(\alpha)}.
v\in V.
L(v)=dL(\alpha)
d\in\mathbb R\\\implies L(v-d\alpha)=0\\\implies T(v-d\alpha)=0\\\implies T(v)=dT(\alpha)\\\implies T(v)=cdL(\alpha)\\\implies T(v)=cL(v)\\\implies T=cL
